# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: engine-knocking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:engine-knocking/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:engine-knocking/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:engine-knocking/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:engine-knocking/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:engine-knocking/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:engine-knocking/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:engine-knocking/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:engine-knocking/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:engine-knocking/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:engine-knocking/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:engine-knocking/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] An **antiknock agent** (or **knock inhibitor**) is a gasoline additive used to reduce engine knocking and increase the fuel's octane rating by raising the temperature and pressure at which auto-ignition occurs.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The mixture known as gasoline or petrol, when used in high compression internal combustion engines, has a tendency to knock (also called "pinging" or "pinking") and/or to ignite early before the correctly timed spark occurs (*pre-ignition*, refer to engine knocking).
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Notable early antiknock agents, especially tetraethyllead, added to gasoline included large amounts of toxic lead.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Some other chemicals used as gasoline additives are thought to be less toxic.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In Europe, after the earlier ban of lead antiknock additives, an effective ban of other metal-contained additives (MFA, metallic fuel additives) was established in 2004 with a specific limit for methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl (MMT) of 6 mg/l from 2011, lowered to 2 mg/l in 2014.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In recent years no use of MMT has been reported in the annual monitoring reports under the European fuel quality directive.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] By the end of the 1990s, North American refineries also voluntary stopped the use of MMT in petrol, since less contested antiknock additives and compounds, such as MTBE and ethanol, were available.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Gibson and Harry Ricardo in England and Thomas Midgley Jr. and Thomas Boyd in the United States.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The discovery that lead additives modified this behavior led to the widespread adoption of the practice in the 1920s and therefore more powerful higher compression engines.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The most popular additive was tetraethyllead.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] However, with the discovery of the environmental and health damage caused by the lead, attributed to Derek Bryce-Smith and Clair Cameron Patterson, and the incompatibility of lead with catalytic converters found on virtually all US automobiles since 1975, this practice began to wane in the 1980s.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Most countries are phasing out leaded fuel although different additives still contain lead compounds.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Other additives include aromatic hydrocarbons, ethers and alcohol (usually ethanol or methanol).
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In the U.S., where tetraethyllead had been blended with gasoline (primarily to boost octane levels) since the early 1920s, standards to phase out leaded gasoline were first implemented in 1973.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In 1995, leaded fuel accounted for only 0.6% of total gasoline sales and less than 2,000 tons of lead per year.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] From January 1, 1996, the Clean Air Act banned the sale of leaded fuel for use in on-road vehicles in the United States.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Possession and use of leaded gasoline in a regular on-road vehicle now carries a maximum US$10,000 fine in the United States.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] However, fuel containing lead may continue to be sold for off-road uses, including aircraft, racing cars, farm equipment, and marine engines.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The ban on leaded gasoline led to thousands fewer tons of lead being released into the air by automobiles.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Similar bans in other countries have resulted in sharply decreasing levels of lead in people's bloodstreams.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] A side effect of the lead additives was protection of the valve seats from erosion.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Many classic cars' engines have needed modification to use lead-free fuels since leaded fuels became unavailable.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] However, "lead substitute" products are also produced and can sometimes be found at auto parts stores.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Gasoline, as delivered at the pump, also contains additives to reduce internal engine carbon buildups, improve combustion, and to allow easier starting in cold climates.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In some parts of South America, Asia, and the Middle East, leaded gasoline is still in use.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Leaded gasoline was phased out in sub-Saharan Africa, starting 1 January 2006.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] A growing number of countries have drawn up plans to ban leaded gasoline in the near future.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Some experts speculate that leaded petrol was behind a global crime wave in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] To avoid deposits of lead inside the engine, lead scavengers are added to the gasoline together with tetraethyllead.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] As tetraethyllead use declined, industry had to decide how to make up the octane deficit between the principal marketable light fuels produced by their refineries, and the higher octane fuels needed for high-compression gasoline engines in the automobile fleet.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Around 70% of the difference was accommodated by more advanced processes at the refinery stage, cracking other hydrocarbon products from the distillation stack to modify them into fuels that would blend gasoline closer the appropriate octane.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Most of the rest of the octane deficit required chemical additives not derived from the refinery process.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Tetraethyl lead was largely replaced in the US with methyl tert-butyl ether starting in 1979.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] MTBE is a toxic water pollutant, and a series of groundwater contamination scandals starting in the 90's prompted the EPA to begin phasing MTBE out in 2000.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Ethanol has several issues as an antiknock additive.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] It is hydrophilic, pulling water vapor out of moist air, and it also increases the level of free oxygen in the fuel significantly.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Both of these cause significant degradation to traditionally constructed engines, posing both residue and corrosion issues in increasing proportion with increasing fractions of ethanol.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Whereas age-degraded gasoline may simply polymerize, evaporate, and thus lose its flammability, age-degraded gasoline-ethanol blends can cause severe damage if allowed to sit in an engine.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Automotive engines addressed this with the mandated shift over to ethanol-tolerant metals and seals, and with the use of smart electronic fuel injection, which has some flexibility to adjust combustion properties and timing.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Automotive engines did not see major issues because of these factors, and because automobiles in active use typically cycle through their gas tank in a matter of weeks.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In small carburetor engines, like generators and lawnmowers, ethanol damage became the dominant mode of failure.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl (MMT) has been used for many years in Canada and recently in Australia to boost octane ratings.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] It also allows old cars, designed to use leaded fuel, to run on unleaded fuel without the need for additives to prevent valve seat erosion.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] A large Canadian study from 2002 (funded by automakers, who are against its use) concluded that MMT impairs the effectiveness of automobile emission controls and increases pollution from motor vehicles.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Many studies have been undertaken over time that confirmed the use of MMT is compatible with vehicles and safe for human health and the environment.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In particular, a 2013 risk assessment on MMT was undertaken by ARCADIS Consulting, following a methodology developed by the European Commission.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] This risk assessment was verified by an independent panel and found by the EU Commission to be compliant with their methodology.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] MMT is manufactured by reduction of bis(methylcyclopentadienyl) manganese using triethylaluminium.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The reduction is conducted under an atmosphere of carbon monoxide.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] MMT is a so-called half-sandwich compound, or more specifically a piano-stool complex (since the three CO ligands are like the legs of a piano stool).
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The manganese atom in MMT is coordinated with three carbonyl groups as well as to the methylcyclopentadienyl ring.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] These hydrophobic organic ligands make MMT highly lipophilic, which may increase bioaccumulation.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] While the structure of MMT suggests lipophilicity and potential to bioaccumulate, comparison of bioconcentration factors (BCF) reported for plant and animal species in comparison to regulatory-based cutoffs (i.e., US EPA and EU REACH) indicates a low bioaccumulative potential of MMT.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Figures 2 and 3 of the study (pages 182 & 184) shows the BCF plotted against time and illustrates the potential BCF of MMT.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] From these figures, the upper curve (A) demonstrates the 9-day MMT BCF plateauing at approximately 400 in plants and 200 in fish, with both values well below the Bioaccumulative / Very Bioaccumulative (B/vB) thresholds of US EPA, EU REACH and Environment & Climate Change Canada.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] A variety of related complexes are known, including ferrocene, which is also under consideration as an additive to gasoline.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Ferrocene is the organometallic compound with the formula Fe(C5H5)2.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] It is the prototypical metallocene, a type of organometallic chemical compound consisting of two cyclopentadienyl rings bound on opposite sides of a central metal atom.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Such organometallic compounds are also known as sandwich compounds.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The rapid growth of organometallic chemistry is often attributed to the excitement arising from the discovery of ferrocene and its many analogues.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Ferrocene and its numerous derivatives have no large-scale applications, but have many niche uses that exploit their unusual structure (ligand scaffolds, pharmaceutical candidates), robustness (anti-knock formulations, precursors to materials), and redox reactions (reagents and redox standards).
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Use for global cooling has been proposed.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Ferrocene and its derivatives are antiknock agents added to the petrol used in motor vehicles, and are safer than the now-banned tetraethyllead.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Petrol additive solutions containing ferrocene can be added to unleaded petrol to enable its use in vintage cars designed to run on leaded petrol.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The iron-containing deposits formed from ferrocene can form a conductive coating on the spark plug surfaces.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Iron pentacarbonyl, also known as iron carbonyl, is the compound with formula Fe(CO)5.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Under standard conditions Fe(CO)5 is a free-flowing, straw-colored liquid with a pungent odour.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] This compound is a common precursor to diverse iron compounds, including many that are useful in organic synthesis.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Fe(CO)5 is prepared by the reaction of fine iron particles with carbon monoxide.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Iron pentacarbonyl is one of the homoleptic metal carbonyls; i.e. metal complexes bonded only to CO ligands.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Other examples include octahedral Cr(CO)6 and tetrahedral Ni(CO)4.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Most metal carbonyls have 18 valence electrons, and Fe(CO)5 fits this pattern with 8 valence electrons on Fe and five pairs of electrons provided by the CO ligands.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Reflecting its symmetrical structure and charge neutrality, Fe(CO)5 is volatile; it is one of the most frequently encountered liquid metal complexes.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Fe(CO)5 adopts a trigonal bipyramidal structure with the Fe atom surrounded by five CO ligands: three in equatorial positions and two axially bound.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Fe(CO)5 is the archetypal fluxional molecule due to the rapid interchange of the axial and equatorial CO groups via the Berry mechanism on the NMR timescale.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Consequently, the13C NMR spectrum exhibits only one signal due to the rapid interchange between nonequivalent CO sites.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In Europe, iron pentacarbonyl was once used as an anti-knock agent in petrol in place of tetraethyllead.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Two more modern alternative fuel additives are ferrocene and methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Fe(CO)5 is used in the production of "carbonyl iron", a finely divided form of iron used in magnetic cores of high-frequency coils for electronics, and for manufacture of the active ingredients of some radar absorbent materials (e.g. iron ball paint).
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] It is famous as a chemical precursor for the synthesis of various iron-based nanoparticles.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Iron pentacarbonyl has been found to be a strong flame speed inhibitor in oxygen based flames.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Toluene is a clear, water-insoluble liquid with a slightly sweet, highly volatile odor reminiscent of paint thinners or other organic solvents.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] It is an aromatic hydrocarbon that is widely used as an industrial feedstock and as a solvent.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Like other solvents, toluene is also used as an inhalant drug for its intoxicating properties.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Toluene and benzene were used as octane rating boosters for aviation fuel by the Royal Air Force in the World War Two.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Tetraethyl lead was manufactured in the USA and was on short supply, so Rolls-Royce engineers built the Rolls-Royce Merlin to work with fuel affed with benzene and toluene.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The Allison V-1710 engine would not run with the RAF fuels as it required tetraethyl lead for lubrication of its valvetrain, but the Packard-built Merlins would.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] This is why the Merlin-engine P-51 Mustangs had a text "Suitable for Aromatics" on their USAAF type description.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Toluene can be used as an octane booster in gasoline fuels used in internal combustion engines.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Toluene at 86% by volume fueled all the turbo Formula 1 teams in the 1980s, first pioneered by the Honda team.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The remaining 14% was a "filler" of n-heptane, to reduce the octane to meet Formula 1 fuel restrictions.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Toluene also poses similar problems as alcohol fuels, as it eats through standard rubber fuel lines and has no lubricating properties as standard gasoline does, which can break down fuel pumps and cause upper cylinder bore wear.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Toluene has also been used as a coolant for its good heat transfer capabilities in sodium cold traps used in nuclear reactor system loops.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Properties of xylenes and ethylbenzene are nearly identical to toluene, with the latter advertised by a refinery as "component of high performance fuels".
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Isooctane is produced on a massive scale in the petroleum industry, usually as a mixture with related hydrocarbons.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The alkylation process alkylates isobutane with isobutylene using a strong acid catalyst.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In the NExOCTANE process, isobutylene is dimerized into isooctene and then hydrogenated to isooctane.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] In World War II, xylidine was an important antiknock agent in very high performance aviation gasolines.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] Its purpose was to permit high levels of boost pressure in multiple-stage turbochargers, and thus high power at high altitudes, without causing detonation that would destroy the engine.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] The high pressures brought high temperatures of inlet air, making engines prone to knock.
[src:engine-knocking/antiknock-agent] This use and storage stabilization methods were important military secrets.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] The fuel–air charge is meant to be ignited by the spark plug only, and at a precise point in the piston's stroke.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Knock occurs when the peak of the combustion process no longer occurs at the optimum moment for the four-stroke cycle.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] The shock wave creates the characteristic metallic "pinging" sound, and cylinder pressure increases dramatically.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Effects of engine knocking range from inconsequential to completely destructive.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Knocking should not be confused with pre-ignition—they are two separate events.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] However, pre-ignition can be followed by knocking.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] The phenomenon of detonation was described in November 1914 in a letter from Lodge Brothers (spark plug manufacturers, and sons of Sir Oliver Lodge) settling a discussion regarding the cause of "knocking" or "pinging" in motorcycles.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] In the letter they stated that an early ignition can give rise to the gas detonating instead of the usual expansion, and the sound that is produced by the detonation is the same as if the metal parts had been tapped with a hammer.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] It was further investigated and described by Harry Ricardo during experiments carried out between 1916 and 1919 to discover the reason for failures in aircraft engines.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Under regular operating conditions, an internal combustion engine burns the air/fuel mixture in the cylinder in an orderly and controlled fashion.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] The combustion is started by the spark plug some 10 to 40 crankshaft degrees prior to top dead center (TDC), depending on many factors including engine speed and load.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] This ignition advance allows time for the combustion process to develop peak pressure at the ideal time for maximum recovery of work from the expanding gases.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] The spark across the spark plug's electrodes forms a small kernel of flame approximately the size of the spark plug gap.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] As it grows in size, its heat output increases, which allows it to grow at an accelerating rate, expanding rapidly through the combustion chamber.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] In normal combustion, this flame front moves throughout the air/fuel mixture at a rate characteristic for the particular mixture.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Pressure rises smoothly to a peak, as nearly all the available fuel is consumed, then pressure falls as the piston descends.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] When unburned fuel–air mixture beyond the boundary of the flame front is subjected to a combination of heat and pressure for a certain duration (beyond the delay period of the fuel used), detonation may occur.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Detonation is characterized by an almost instantaneous, explosive ignition of at least one pocket of air/fuel mixture outside of the flame front.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] A local shockwave is created around each pocket, and the cylinder pressure will rise sharply – and possibly beyond its design limits – causing damage.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] If detonation is allowed to persist under extreme conditions or over many engine cycles, engine parts can be damaged or destroyed.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] The simplest deleterious effect is particle wear caused by moderate knocking, with the resulting particulate dispersing into the engine's oil system causing abrasive wear on other parts prior to being trapped by the oil filter.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Such wear gives the appearance of erosion, abrasion, or a "sandblasted" look, similar to the damage caused by hydraulic cavitation.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Hypereutectic pistons are known to break easily from such shock waves.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] The addition of tetraethyl lead (TEL), a soluble organolead compound added to gasoline, was common until it was discontinued for reasons of toxic pollution.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Lead dust added to the intake charge will also reduce knock with various hydrocarbon fuels.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Manganese compounds are also used to reduce knock with petrol fuel.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] As an aftermarket solution, a water injection system can be employed to reduce combustion chamber peak temperatures and thus suppress detonation.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Steam (water vapor) will suppress knock even though no added cooling is supplied.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Turbulence has an important effect on knock.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Engines with good turbulence tend to knock less than engines with poor turbulence.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Turbulence occurs not only while the engine is inhaling but also when the mixture is compressed and burned.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Many pistons are designed to use "squish" turbulence to violently mix the air and fuel together as they are ignited and burned, which reduces knock greatly by speeding up burning and cooling the unburnt mixture.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] One example of this is all modern side valve or flathead engines.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] A considerable portion of the head space is made to come in close proximity to the piston crown, making for much turbulence near TDC.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] In the early days of side valve heads this was not done and a much lower compression ratio had to be used for any given fuel.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Also such engines were sensitive to ignition advance and had less power.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Knocking is more or less unavoidable in diesel engines, where fuel is injected into highly compressed air towards the end of the compression stroke.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] There is a short lag between the fuel being injected and combustion starting.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] By this time there is already a quantity of fuel in the combustion chamber which will ignite first in areas of greater oxygen density prior to the combustion of the complete charge.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] This sudden increase in pressure and temperature causes the distinctive diesel 'knock' or 'clatter', some of which must be allowed for in the engine design.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Careful design of the injector pump, fuel injector, combustion chamber, piston crown and cylinder head can reduce knocking greatly, and modern engines using electronic common rail injection have very low levels of knock.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Engines using indirect injection generally have lower levels of knock than direct injection engines, due to the greater dispersal of oxygen in the combustion chamber and lower injection pressures providing a more complete mixing of fuel and air.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Diesels actually do not suffer exactly the same "knock" as gasoline engines since the cause is known to be only the very fast rate of pressure rise, not unstable combustion.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Diesel fuels are actually very prone to knock in gasoline engines but in the diesel engine there is no time for knock to occur because the fuel is only oxidized during the expansion cycle.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] In the gasoline engine the fuel is slowly oxidizing all the time while it is being compressed before the spark.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] This allows for changes to occur in the structure/makeup of the molecules before the very critical period of high temperature/pressure.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Due to the large variation in fuel quality, atmospheric pressure, and ambient temperature as well as the possibility of a malfunction, every modern combustion engine contains mechanisms to detect and prevent knocking.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] A control loop permanently monitors the signal of one or more **knock sensors** (commonly piezoelectric sensors which are able to translate vibrations into an electric signal).
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] If the characteristic pressure peak of a knocking combustion is detected, the ignition timing is retarded by steps of a few degrees.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] If the signal normalizes indicating a controlled combustion the ignition timing is advanced again in the same fashion keeping the engine at its best possible operating point - the so-called ″knock limit″.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Modern knock control-loop systems are able to adjust ignition timings for every cylinder individually.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Depending on the specific engine the boost pressure is regulated simultaneously.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] This way performance is kept at its optimum while mostly eliminating the risk of engine damage caused by knock (e.g. when running on low octane fuel).
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] An early example of this is in turbocharged Saab H engines, where a system called Automatic Performance Control was used to reduce boost pressure if it caused the engine to knock.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Since the avoidance of knocking combustion is so important to development engineers, a variety of simulation technologies have been developed which can identify engine design or operating conditions in which knock might be expected to occur.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] This then enables engineers to design ways to mitigate knocking combustion whilst maintaining a high thermal efficiency.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] The objective of knock control is to attempt to optimize the trade-off between protecting the engine from damaging knock events and maximizing the engine's output torque.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Knock events are an independent random process.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] It is impossible to design knock controllers in a deterministic platform.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] A single time history simulation or experiment of knock control methods are not able to provide a repeatable measurement of controller's performance because of the random nature of arriving knock events.
[src:engine-knocking/engine-knocking] Therefore, the desired trade-off must be done in a stochastic framework which could provide a suitable environment for designing and evaluating different knock control strategies performances with rigorous statistical properties.
